body:
The following test fails due to ordering failing to track partial variable assignments.

If you swap in the commented out alternate assignment, which has a lower fan-in, it will happen to order correctly.

Options: `--cc --exe --timing --build -fno-dfg -fno-split bad.sv bad.cpp`

EDIT: You also need `-fno-var-split` on latest master to reproduce this.

bad.sv:

```systemverilog
module bad(
  // Input and ouput
  input logic i,
  output logic o,
  // Dummies to increase fan-in of assignment - always set to 1
  input logic const_1_a,
  input logic const_1_b,
  input logic const_1_c
);

  logic [2:0] s = 3'b0;

  // This always, and the assign below together should make 'o' always equal to '~i'
  always_comb begin
    s[1:0] = 2'b0;
    if (i) begin
      s[1:0] = 2'b1;
      o = 1'b0;
    end else begin
      o = s[2];
    end
  end

  // If you just use this, it happens to order correctly, as this assign has
  // lower fan-in + fan-out than the always block
  //assign s[2] = ~i;
  // If you use this, it breaks, as the increased fan-in changes ordering
  assign s[2] = ~i & const_1_a & const_1_b & const_1_c;

endmodule
```

bad.cpp:

```c++
// Verilated -*- C++ -*-
// DESCRIPTION: main() calling loop, created with Verilator --main

#include <cassert>
#include <cstdio>

#include "verilated.h"
#include "Vbad.h"

//======================

int main(int argc, char** argv, char**) {
    // Setup context, defaults, and parse command line
    Verilated::debug(0);
    const std::unique_ptr<VerilatedContext> contextp{new VerilatedContext};
    contextp->commandArgs(argc, argv);

    // Construct the Verilated model, from Vtop.h generated from Verilating
    const std::unique_ptr<Vbad> topp{new Vbad{contextp.get(), ""}};

    topp->const_1_a = 1;
    topp->const_1_b = 1;
    topp->const_1_c = 1;

    for (int n = 0; n < 10; ++n) {
      topp->i = 0;
      topp->eval();
      printf("i: %d o: %d\n", topp->i, topp->o);
      assert(topp->o == 1);

      topp->i = 1;
      topp->eval();
      printf("i: %d o: %d\n", topp->i, topp->o);
      assert(topp->o == 0);
    }
    return 0;
}
```

There is no UNOPFLAT warning, and you can see the order graph does not define ordering between the always block and the continuous assignment:

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a814d370-efbb-4437-81df-b977c574a13a)

I suspect this is due to the following assumption, and tracking variables as a whole, but this one is actually synthesizeable:
https://github.com/verilator/verilator/blob/258becd179b04bf2f290035741432d39cbf1d213/src/V3OrderGraphBuilder.cpp#L196-L209

This again is from some 140k line codebase and is a right pain to find. I only did because -fno-dfg changes the fanin/fanout of some assignments and I manged to hit a working case to diff waves against. We should fix the TODO below, but even with that you need to make conservative assumptions if you have selects with a variable index on the LHS of assignment. Or at least some sort of warning would be nice here 🙁

